         <div type="edition" xml:lang="san-Latn" rendition="class:83227 maturity:83213">
            <lg n="1" met="anuṣṭubh">
                <l n="a"><lb n="1"/>@ purā rājādhirājena</l> 
                <l n="b">guruṇā pīna-bāhunā</l>
                <l n="c">khātā khyātāṁ purīṁ prāpya</l> 
                <l n="d"><lb n="2"/>candrabhāgārṇṇavaṁ yayau ||</l>
            </lg>
                <!-- @: a sign that might represent a fly-whisk, a very stylized triśāla, or "a burning torch" (Sarkar, p. 5 and his n. 26).
                b. guruṇā: Chhabra Sarkar; gurunā Vogel (probably a misprint). See guṇaujasā in l. 2 for the shape of gu.
                c. khyātāṁ purīṁ: thus Vogel (see his remark on the notation of anusvāra, p. 33: "In the first instance, it is marked by means of a dot, in the second by a dot enclosed within a circle"); khyātām purīm Chhabra Sarkar.
                d. °bhāgārṇṇavaṁ: thus Vogel (see his note, p. 33); ̌°bhāgārṇṇavam Chhabra Sarkar.
                ||: Vogel Sarkar; omitted by Chhabra. -->
            <lg n="2" met="anuṣṭubh">
                    <l n="a" enjamb="yes">pravarddhamāna-dvāviṅśad</l>
                    <l n="b">-vatsara śrī-guṇaujasā</l>
                    <l n="c">narendra-dhvaja-bhātena</l> 
                    <l n="d"><lb n="3"/>śrīmatā pūrṇṇavarmmaṇo ||</l>
            </lg>
                <!-- a. °vatsara: °vatsa(re) Vogel (see his n., p. 33); °vatsare Chhabra; "Read °śare" (Sarkar, misprint). 
                c. °bhātena: Sarkar; °bhānena (bhātena) Vogel; °bhāne(te)na Chhabra. See Sarkar n. 30: "Te is however certain. In this inscription, ta is distinguished from na by the slightly triangular form it (ta) betrays."
                d. °varmmaṇo: °varmmaṇā Vogel. The element that seems to form the e-mātrā is not likely to be accidental. Cf. the ṇai is l. 5.
                ||: Vogel Sarkar; omitted by Chhabra. -->
            <lg n="3" met="anuṣṭubh">
                <l n="a">prārabhya phālguṇe māse</l> 
                <l n="b">khātā kr̥ṣṇāṣṭamī-tithau</l>
                <l n="c">caitra-śukla-trayodaśyāM</l> 
                <l n="d">dinais siddhaikaviṅśakai<supplied reason="lost">ḥ ||</supplied></l>
            </lg>
                <!-- a. phālguṇe: phālguṇe(ne) Vogel Chhabra Sarkar. It is unnecessary to correct to phālgune, the variant with retroflex nasal being extremely common in Southeast Asian epigraphy (Cambodia, Campa) as in India.
                b. kr̥ṣṇāṣṭamī°: as pointed out by Sarkar (n. 32), Vogel's kr̥ṣṇātaṣmī° must be a misprint.
                c. caitra°: Vogel and Sarkar have expressed doubt about the ai (suspecting rather e), but the ai seems certain to me, in comparison with dinais and °viṅśakai further on in this line.
                d. dinais: thus do Vogel, Chhabra and Sarkar read; the n is rather unclear, but no other reading is imaginable.
                d. °viṅśakai[ḥ ||]: Vogel (p. 33) thinks the visarga can still be traced; Chhabra assumes one without question; Sarkar thinks is invisible but needs to be restored; I do not see it. All ignore the fact that a pair of daṇ.das must also have been lost.
                 -->
            <lg n="4" met="anuṣṭubh">
                <l n="a"><lb n="4"/>Āyatā ṣaṭ-sahasreṇa</l> 
                <l n="b">dhanuṣā<supplied reason="lost">ṁ</supplied> saśatena ca</l>
                <l n="c">dvāviṅśena nadī ramyā</l> 
                <l n="d">gomatī nirmalodakā ||</l>
            </lg>
                <!-- 
                    b. dhanuṣā[ṁ] saśatena: Chhabra; dhanuṣā(m) saśatena Sarkar; dhanuṣā[ṁ]sa-śatena Vogel. The anusvāra is not visible.
                 -->
            <lg n="5" met="anuṣṭubh">
                    <l n="a">pitāmahasya rājarṣer</l> 
                    <l n="b">vvidāryya śibirāvani<supplied reason="lost">M</supplied></l>
                    <l n="c"><lb n="5"/>brāhmaṇair go-sahasre<choice><sic>nā</sic><corr>ṇa</corr></choice></l>
                    <l n="d">prayāti kr̥ta-dakṣiṇā || ... || @ || ... ||</l>
            </lg>
               <!--  
                b. vvidāryya: Chhabra Sarkar; vvidārya Vogel.
                b. śibirāvani[M]: śibirāvanim Vogel Chhabra Sarkar; none observes that the final nasal (presumably written in reduced size below the baseline, as in l. 3) is invisible, at least on POD, pl. 27. Sarkar's note 37 (although marred by several disturbing misprints/errors) makes the valid point that the reading in fact seems to be śī°. Since śi° is the desired reading, and since this inscription does not otherwise commit errors involving vowel length, I assume the trace that would distinguish ī from i is accidental.
                c. °sahasrenā: corr. °sahasreṇa (with Vogel Chhabra Sarkar).
                d. kr̥tadakṣiṇā: kr̥tadakṣiṇo Vogel.
                || ... || @ || ... ||: an elaborate final punctuation, ignored by Vogel, Chhabra and Sarkar. -->
